<h2>Frequently Asked Questions {#frequently-asked-questions}</h2>
<h3><strong>Q: At what age should seniors get their hearing tested?</strong></h3>
<p>Screening for hearing loss is recommended in adults older than 50 to 60 years. Annual testing is advisable after age 65, or sooner if you notice changes.</p>
<h3><strong>Q: Why doesn&#39;t Medicare cover hearing aids?</strong></h3>
<p>Medicare Parts A and B do not currently cover the cost of hearing aids. This exclusion dates back to Medicare&#39;s creation in 1965. However, proposed legislation like the Medicare Hearing Aid Coverage Act of 2025 aims to change this.</p>
<h3><strong>Q: What percentage of seniors who need hearing aids actually use them?</strong></h3>
<p>Unfortunately, only 20% of those individuals who might benefit from treatment actually seek help. This represents a significant gap in hearing healthcare for seniors.</p>
<h3><strong>Q: Can untreated hearing loss affect cognitive health?</strong></h3>
<p>Yes. Untreated hearing loss has been linked to issues such as sadness, depression, anxiety, paranoia, cognitive decline, and poor social relationships. Research shows addressing hearing loss may help maintain cognitive function.</p>
<h3><strong>Q: How long does it take to adjust to hearing aids?</strong></h3>
<p>Most seniors need 2-4 weeks for initial adjustment, though full adaptation can take 2-3 months. The brain needs time to relearn how to process sounds it hasn&#39;t heard clearly in years.</p>
<h3><strong>Q: Are expensive hearing aids worth it for seniors?</strong></h3>
<p>It depends on individual needs. More expensive hearing aids may come with extra features such as Bluetooth wireless connectivity and tinnitus masking. However, many seniors find satisfaction with affordable OTC options.</p>
<h3><strong>Q: What&#39;s the difference between hearing amplifiers and hearing aids?</strong></h3>
<p>Hearing aids are FDA-regulated medical devices designed for hearing loss. Amplifiers simply make all sounds louder and aren&#39;t recommended for hearing loss. Seniors should choose FDA-cleared OTC hearing aids or prescription devices.</p>
<h3><strong>Q: Can earwax cause hearing problems in seniors?</strong></h3>
<p>Yes, earwax buildup is common in older adults and can worsen hearing. Always have ears checked before purchasing hearing aids, as simple wax removal might improve hearing significantly.</p>
<h3><strong>Q: Do all Medicare Advantage plans cover hearing aids?</strong></h3>
<p>No, coverage varies significantly. During open enrollment, carefully compare plans&#39; hearing benefits, including coverage amounts, copays, and provider networks.</p>
<h3><strong>Q: What if a senior can&#39;t afford any hearing aids?</strong></h3>
<p>Explore options like:</p>
<ul>
